{
  "texts": [
    "In this case, the space spanned by the rows of C has dimension n -1, implying there exists a unique (up to scaling) linear dependence among the n rows.",
    "We can write this, representing the ith row as r i ∈ {0, 1} n, asn-1 i=0 α i r i = {0} n, for some α = (α 0,... α n-1) ∈ {0, 1} n, α ̸ = {0} n,(51)By the rank-nullity theorem, if a matrix has rank m over {0, 1}, then its kernel has dimension n -m, and hence size 2 n-m.",
    "Therefore, since C m has rank m, its kernel has size 2 n-m.",
    "Applying Lemma 4, we obtainp CmY ({0} m) = 2 n-m 2 n = 2 -m,(58)as required.Now, we have the ingredients to prove the main theorem, Theorem 9, which follows directly from Theorem 15 and Corollary 5.6.1 from [19].",
    "A.4 Dodis et al."
  ]
}